\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01FawyThCqUzJMB8RbRavrCK\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Now I have a complete picture. Let me compile the comprehensive analysis.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Detailed Analysis: Why 95 Real Sessions Take 25.5s vs 100 Test Sessions Taking ~1.3s\\n\\n### 1. `listAllSessionStates` -- O(N) `repo.Reference()` for EVERY session\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/evisdrenova/code/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_session.go`, lines 60-102\\n\\nFor every session state file, `listAllSessionStates` does:\\n1. **File I/O**: `store.List()` reads the `.git/entire-sessions/` directory, then `os.ReadFile` + `json.Unmarshal` for each `.json` file (N file reads).\\n2. **Git ref lookup**: `repo.Reference(refName, true)` for the shadow branch `entire/<hash>-<worktreeID>` -- one go-git reference resolution **per session**.\\n\\n```go\\nfor _, sessionState := range sessionStates {\\n    shadowBranch := getShadowBranchNameForCommit(state.BaseCommit, state.WorktreeID)\\n    refName := plumbing.NewBranchReferenceName(shadowBranch)\\n    if _, err := repo.Reference(refName, true); err != nil {  // <-- PER SESSION\\n        if !state.Phase.IsActive() && state.LastCheckpointID.IsEmpty() {\\n            store.Clear(ctx, state.SessionID)  // cleanup orphan\\n            continue\\n        }\\n    }\\n    states = append(states, state)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nFor ENDED sessions with `LastCheckpointID` set (the 88 ended sessions in the real scenario), the shadow branch ref lookup **still happens**, it just doesn't trigger cleanup because the `if` condition fails (LastCheckpointID is non-empty). The reference lookup fails (branch doesn't exist for ended sessions), and go-git has to search through packed refs to determine that. **This is 88 failed ref lookups.**\\n\\n**Test difference**: The test at `/Users/evisdrenova/code/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/commit_hook_perf_test.go` line 267-291 creates ENDED sessions with `LastCheckpointID` set and no shadow branch, which is correct. But the test repo is tiny -- a freshly created temp repo with no packed refs and a minimal `.git` directory. In a real repo, reference resolution is much slower.\\n\\n### 2. `listAllSessionStates` is called MULTIPLE TIMES per commit\\n\\nThis is critical. Let me trace the call chain:\\n\\n**PrepareCommitMsg flow:**\\n1. `PrepareCommitMsg` -> `findSessionsForWorktree` -> **`listAllSessionStates`** (1st call) -- lines 337-338\\n2. `filterSessionsWithNewContent` -> per-session `sessionHasNewContent` -> shadow branch ref lookups (additional git ops)\\n3. `getLastPrompt` -> per session, another `repo.Reference` for shadow branch (line 1846)\\n\\n**PostCommit flow:**\\n4. `PostCommit` -> `findSessionsForWorktree` -> **`listAllSessionStates`** (2nd call) -- line 739\\n5. Per-session in the loop: `postCommitProcessSession` does another `repo.Reference` per session (line 840)\\n\\n**No-trailer path (postCommitUpdateBaseCommitOnly):**\\n6. `postCommitUpdateBaseCommitOnly` -> `findSessionsForWorktree` -> **`listAllSessionStates`** (also called if no trailer)\\n\\nEach `listAllSessionStates` call does N `repo.Reference` lookups. With 95 sessions called twice (PrepareCommitMsg + PostCommit), that's **190 reference lookups just for the listing step**, plus the per-session lookups in the processing loops.\\n\\n### 3. `filterSessionsWithNewContent` -- O(N) per session with expensive git ops\\n\\n**Location:** lines 1098-1114 of `manual_commit_hooks.go`\\n\\nCalled during PrepareCommitMsg for ALL sessions returned by `findSessionsForWorktree`. For each session:\\n\\n```go\\nfor _, state := range sessions {\\n    hasNew, err := s.sessionHasNewContent(ctx, repo, state)  // <-- per session\\n    ...\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**`sessionHasNewContent`** (lines 1120-1248) does for each session:\\n\\n- **If no cached shadow tree**: `repo.Reference()` + `repo.CommitObject()` + `commit.Tree()` -- 3 git object lookups per session\\n- **If shadow branch exists**: reads transcript file content from the tree via `tree.File()` + `file.Contents()` -- decompresses the blob\\n- **If no shadow branch**: falls through to `sessionHasNewContentFromLiveTranscript` which does file I/O (reads the live transcript from disk) and transcript parsing\\n- **For carry-forward sessions**: calls `getStagedFiles(repo)` which calls `worktree.Status()` -- this computes a **full git status** which is expensive (O(files in worktree))\\n- **Content-aware overlap**: `stagedFilesOverlapWithContent` does per-file content comparison\\n\\n**For ENDED sessions (88 of them):**\\nIn `postCommitProcessSession`, ENDED sessions with `state.Phase.IsActive() == false` go through the else branch (line 864-873):\\n```go\\nhasNew, contentErr = s.sessionHasNewContent(ctx, repo, state, shadowTree)\\n```\\nThis resolves the shadow branch ref (fails), falls through to `sessionHasNewContentFromLiveTranscript`, which checks `state.TranscriptPath`. If empty, returns false. But each one still attempts the ref lookup.\\n\\n### 4. `postCommitProcessSession` -- Per-session git operations in PostCommit\\n\\n**Location:** lines 818-962\\n\\nFor EACH of the 95 sessions, PostCommit does:\\n1. `getShadowBranchNameForCommit` -- string computation (cheap)\\n2. `repo.Reference(shadowBranchName)` -- **git ref lookup** (line 840)\\n3. If ref found: `repo.CommitObject(ref.Hash())` + `commit.Tree()` -- **2 more git object lookups**\\n4. For non-ACTIVE sessions: `sessionHasNewContent()` -- more git ops as described above\\n5. For ACTIVE sessions with empty FilesTouched: `extractFilesFromLiveTranscript()` -- reads transcript file + parses JSON\\n6. State machine transition + handler invocation\\n7. If condensed: `filesWithRemainingAgentChanges()` -- per-file content comparison against shadow branch\\n8. If condensed with remaining files: `carryForwardToNewShadowBranch()` -- creates a git commit (tree building + commit object)\\n9. `saveSessionState()` -- file write per session\\n\\n**For ENDED sessions specifically** (state machine transition `ENDED + GitCommit`):\\n- The handler calls `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched`\\n- If `state.FilesTouched` is non-empty (it is in the real scenario -- 2 files per session), it calls `shouldCondenseWithOverlapCheck`\\n- `shouldCondenseWithOverlapCheck` calls `filesOverlapWithContent` which does content comparison against the shadow branch tree\\n\\nBUT the shadow branch doesn't exist for ENDED sessions, so `filesOverlapWithContent` falls back to a filename-only check (returns `len(filesTouched) > 0` = true). This means **ENDED sessions with FilesTouched may actually get condensed**, triggering the full `CondenseSession` path.\\n\\nWait -- let me re-check. The `shouldCondenseWithOverlapCheck` first checks `hasNew`:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (h *postCommitActionHandler) shouldCondenseWithOverlapCheck(isActive bool) bool {\\n    if !h.hasNew {\\n        return false  // <-- early exit if no new content\\n    }\\n```\\n\\nFor ENDED sessions, `hasNew` is determined by `sessionHasNewContent`. If the shadow branch doesn't exist and there's no live transcript, this returns false. So ENDED sessions **without shadow branches** should get `hasNew=false` and skip condensation.\\n\\nBut they still go through all the git operations to determine that.\\n\\n### 5. Key Differences Between Test and Real-World\\n\\n**a) go-git reference resolution speed**\\n\\nIn the test (temp repo with ~12 branches), `repo.Reference()` is essentially an in-memory lookup. In a real repo with potentially hundreds of refs (local branches, remote tracking branches, tags, other entire/* branches from previous sessions), go-git has to search through packed-refs and loose refs. With 95 sessions, if the repo has 200+ refs total, each reference lookup scans the packed refs file.\\n\\n**b) `.git` directory size and object database**\\n\\nA real repo has thousands of git objects. go-git's `PlainOpenWithOptions` reads the entire pack index into memory. `repo.CommitObject()` and `commit.Tree()` operations involve decompressing objects from packfiles. In a real repo, pack files can be MB or GB in size.\\n\\n**c) `worktree.Status()` in `getStagedFiles()`**\\n\\n`getStagedFiles` calls `worktree.Status()` which does a **full diff between HEAD tree, index, and working directory**. In go-git v5, this is notoriously slow for large repos. In the test, the repo has 5 files. In a real repo, it could have thousands.\\n\\n`getStagedFiles` is called inside `sessionHasNewContent` (via `stagedFilesOverlapWithContent`) for sessions that have carry-forward files or transcript growth. In PrepareCommitMsg, it's called potentially once per session that passes the transcript check. But in PostCommit, `getStagedFiles` returns empty (files already committed), so the call is fast but still invoked.\\n\\n**d) Transcript file reads**\\n\\nFor ACTIVE sessions, `sessionHasNewContentFromLiveTranscript` reads the live transcript file from disk, parses it to count lines, and extracts modified files. A real transcript can be several MB. The test uses a 3-line transcript.\\n\\n**e) `OpenRepository` is called multiple times**\\n\\n`OpenRepository` does `git.PlainOpenWithOptions` each time. In PrepareCommitMsg (line 324) and PostCommit (line 709), the repo is opened independently. Each open loads pack indexes and ref lists.\\n\\n**f) ENDED sessions with FilesTouched**\\n\\nIn the test (line 285), ENDED sessions have `FilesTouched: modifiedFiles` (2 files). In a real scenario, ENDED sessions could have much larger `FilesTouched` arrays -- 10, 20, 50+ files -- accumulated over a long session.\\n\\n### 6. The O(N) Cost Summary\\n\\nFor a commit with 95 sessions (88 ended, 6 idle, 1 active), here is the per-operation count:\\n\\n| Operation | PrepareCommitMsg | PostCommit | Total |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| `store.List()` (read N JSON files) | 1x (95 reads) | 1x (95 reads) | 190 file reads |\\n| `repo.Reference()` in `listAllSessionStates` | 95 lookups | 95 lookups | 190 ref lookups |\\n| `repo.Reference()` in `postCommitProcessSession` | -- | 95 lookups | 95 ref lookups |\\n| `repo.Reference()` in `sessionHasNewContent` | up to 95 | up to 95 | up to 190 ref lookups |\\n| `repo.CommitObject()` + `.Tree()` per session | varies | 95 (if refs exist) | varies |\\n| `getStagedFiles()` -> `worktree.Status()` | up to 95 calls | 0 (empty post-commit) | up to 95 status calls |\\n| `getLastPrompt()` ref lookup | 1 (first session) | -- | 1 |\\n| `saveSessionState()` file writes | 0 | 95 writes | 95 file writes |\\n\\n**Conservative estimate**: ~475 git reference lookups + 285 file I/O operations + N `worktree.Status()` calls.\\n\\nAt ~30-50ms per go-git reference lookup in a real repo (packed refs with hundreds of entries), 475 lookups alone = **14-24 seconds**. The `worktree.Status()` calls add more (though they may be internally cached by go-git within the same process).\\n\\n### 7. Why the Test Is Fast (~1.3s)\\n\\nThe test at `/Users/evisdrenova/code/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/commit_hook_perf_test.go`:\\n\\n1. Uses a **fresh temp directory** with a tiny `.git` (no packed refs, tiny object database)\\n2. Has only **5 source files** (fast `worktree.Status()`)\\n3. go-git's `repo.Reference()` is nearly instant with 12 loose refs (no packed-refs file to parse)\\n4. File I/O is on a temp filesystem (likely in memory/SSD buffer)\\n5. The repo has no history (1 commit) so tree operations are trivial\\n6. ENDED sessions have no shadow branch AND the ref lookup fails instantly (no packed-refs to scan)\\n7. Transcript files are 3 lines (trivial to parse)\\n\\n### 8. Recommendations for Investigation\\n\\nThe most impactful optimizations would be:\\n\\n1. **Batch reference resolution**: Instead of calling `repo.Reference()` 95 times, iterate all refs once with `repo.References()` and build a map. This turns O(N * R) into O(R + N) where R is total ref count.\\n\\n2. **Skip ENDED sessions earlier**: ENDED sessions with `LastCheckpointID` set and no shadow branch cannot have new content. They should be filtered out before `postCommitProcessSession` rather than going through the full content-check pipeline.\\n\\n3. **Cache `listAllSessionStates` result**: Since `ManualCommitStrategy` is instantiated fresh for each hook call, the `listAllSessionStates` result is computed twice (once in PrepareCommitMsg, once in PostCommit). Even within PostCommit, `findSessionsForWorktree` -> `listAllSessionStates` is called, and then each session gets more ref lookups.\\n\\n4. **Avoid `worktree.Status()` in PrepareCommitMsg**: `getStagedFiles` is called per-session inside `sessionHasNewContent`. Computing it once and passing it in would eliminate redundant status computations.\\n\\n5. **Prune old session state files**: 88 ENDED sessions persisting in `.git/entire-sessions/` means every hook invocation pays the cost of reading and checking all of them. After condensation, ENDED sessions only need to stick around for `LastCheckpointID` reuse on amend. A TTL-based cleanup (already partially implemented via `IsStale()`) could reduce the working set.\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"agentId: a7c40bfe180456c28 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\\n<usage>total_tokens: 99725\\ntool_uses: 34\\nduration_ms: 160350</usage>\"}]}]},\"uuid\":\"3f2992bf-3f19-4870-b726-d67f01ea72ac\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-27T19:20:03.000Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"prompt\":\"A user with ~95 sessions (88 ended, 6 idle, 1 active) experienced 25.5s commit time. But our performance test with 100 sessions only takes ~1.3s. I need to understand why.\\n\\nInvestigate the following potential differences between the test and real-world scenario:\\n\\n1. **ENDED sessions with shadow branches that still exist** - In the test, ENDED sessions have no shadow branch (only LastCheckpointID). In reality, could ENDED sessions still have shadow branches? Check `listAllSessionStates